{
  "answer": "Open borders are not universally beneficial; outcomes depend on country-specific institutions, labor markets, and public capacity. Evidence on GDP gains and labor-supply expansion is mixed, and long-run effects can differ from short-run projections. Without careful design, fiscal costs, housing shortages, and public-service burdens may erode any gains. A prudent approach uses phased, evidence-driven pilots with clear budgets and robust integration, asylum processing, and housing/education capacity, alongside selective openness by skill, region, or sector. Evaluation should rely on rigorous quasi-experimental analysis, scenario modeling, and predefined decision rules (milestones, budgets, rollback criteria) before scaling. Key design choices—and their interaction with macro conditions—determine net benefits. Operationalization requires explicit categories of openness, clear eligibility rules, and sunset clauses with transparent data dashboards. Data should come from diverse sources, including administrative records and high-quality international databases, but with caveats about comparability. Security, privacy, and asylum processing must be embedded in governance designs and not treated as afterthoughts. Macro feedbacks (inflation, exchange rates, capital flows) should be monitored as part of ongoing assessment. Distributional impacts should be analyzed and mitigated for low-skilled workers and regional economies.",
  "keyClaims": [
    "Economic effects are context-dependent and evidence of universal GDP gains is mixed.",
    "Long-run outcomes depend on capital deepening, productivity, and design.",
    "Fiscal and service costs depend on welfare generosity, integration success, and capacity; explicit budgets and guardrails are needed.",
    "Housing and infrastructure constraints can limit net benefits and must be modeled.",
    "Policy design quality (phased pilots, metrics, evaluation, rollback) largely determines success.",
    "Selective openness by skill, region, or sector should be defined and operationalized with clear rules.",
    "Evaluation frameworks must specify endpoints, data sources, timeframes, and methods.",
    "Pilot results may not generalize due to path dependence and biases; plan for externalities and selection effects.",
    "Data quality caveats apply; avoid overreliance on cross-country aggregates without caveats.",
    "Security, asylum processing, and governance require defined controls, privacy protections, and governance structures.",
    "Macroeconomic feedbacks should be monitored as mobility shocks interact with inflation, exchange rates, and capital flows."
  ],
  "assumptions": [
    "Credible data will be available from multiple sources with appropriate caveats.",
    "Governments can fund housing, infrastructure, and integration capacity at scale if warranted by results.",
    "Political feasibility and legitimacy can be built through stakeholder engagement and transparent evaluation.",
    "Pilot programs can be rolled back or adjusted based on predefined criteria.",
    "Sufficient administrative capacity exists to monitor, enforce, and adjust openness policies."
  ],
  "confidence": 0.44
}

